# Common Mistakes

## 1. Missing Dependencies
If your effect uses a prop or state variable but you omit it from the dependency array, you'll have a **stale closure** – the effect will always see the initial value.

## 2. Infinite Loops
If you update state inside an effect and that state is also a dependency, you can create an infinite loop.

```jsx
// ❌ Infinite loop
useEffect(() => {
  setCount(count + 1); // count changes, effect re-runs
}, [count]);
```

## 3. Object/Function Dependencies
If you use an object or function as a dependency, it changes every render, causing the effect to run every time. Use `useCallback` or `useMemo` to stabilize them.

slides.codeSnippet:
function Counter() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  useEffect(() => {
    const timer = setInterval(() => {
      console.log(count); // Always logs 0 (stale)
    }, 1000);
    return () => clearInterval(timer);
  }, []); // Missing `count` dependency
}
